Though everything was in agreement, everyone knew that Palau’s rich history and long-time cultural beliefs would, one way or another, be tampered by the mabulstructors. The way of life, indigenous education and use of Palauans’ indigenous language, Buong, has greatly changed within a couple of decades. Foreign influences on geo-politics have thus exponentially affected the life and circumstances in the islands.

Global warming and climate change may be the most significant challenges which Palau faces in the light of the next 100 years given the diversity of its small but bountiful barrier reef ecosystem.

The power of our culture in Palau and the broader Pacific will remain with us and those people which maintain its pervasiveness within its dynamic dynamic nature will continue on the current path. Unfortunately those nations which have drastically altered their culture in favor of the capitalist-relative-mode of living since western imperialistic colonization will remain the same, less.

FORESTS AND CROPS

It is very difficult to say when the first forest has stood on land. Such an inquiry is similar to asking when the first war was fought. In all probability, every tiny creature has played a part in all known and undocumented scenarios. One can hazard a guess and the few characteristics that suited the purpose best; i.e., when the Penanta family clan occupied what is now Peleliu.
